      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i see. so basically it just hides the person doing the work. it's more about clarity then anything else. are there any other parts of a sentence that can 'hide' the subject or make things a bit fuzzy like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, there are several other parts of a sentence that can make it harder to identify the subject or create ambiguity. One common example is the use of relative clauses, which can introduce a dependent clause that starts with a relative pronoun like \"who,\" \"which,\" or \"that.\" These clauses can make the sentence structure more complex, but they can also obscure the main subject.\n\nFor instance, consider the sentence: \"The researcher who conducted the experiment is the author of the paper.\" In this sentence, the relative clause \"who conducted the experiment\" is attached to the main clause \"The researcher is the author of the paper.\" While it's clear that the researcher is the subject of the main clause, the relative clause can make it seem like the researcher is the one conducting the experiment, rather than just being the author of the paper.\n\nAnother example is the use of phrases like \"as reported by\" or \"according to.\" These phrases can make it seem like the information is coming from someone else, rather than the author themselves. For example, \"The results are as reported by the previous study\" can make it seem like the author is simply repeating someone else's findings, rather than presenting their own.\n\nIn science writing, it's essential to",
      "source": "target",
